<br>
The original post was well argued and thoughtful. Thats a nice change from most of what i've seen here. I would like to add something with respect to &quot;balancing&quot; in general.<br>
<br>
Being a long term player since the beta I feel this change is just another in a very long line of class and item changes that have been placed upon the playing community without the benefit of input from the majority of those players that will be affected.<br>
<br>
I feel at this time even with new leadership Verant still does not have the insight to understand the &quot;average&quot; players game. A few reason I feel this way:<br>
<br>
Items: Who exactly is designing items and approving them? Why would a level 50 plus helm's only requirement be 20 defense? Why would the Scythe of Sundering, an easy one group encounter, be not level dependant? Thats a 80hp 13 20 with aggro proc weapon. I see a few level 15 warriors with those. /boggle The week my Druid starts camping the Manastone its removed. Too powerfull they say. Hmm, why the new mana conversion robe, especially with the Wizards epic!?<br>
<br>
Skills: Manaburn, what exactly did they expect with this? Certainly makes Wizzies more group friendly. With other Wizards. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Spells: DOT's were nerfed way back when. Friends left the game. Any reason to roll back the change as they did? KEI on level 20's? Soloers paradise!<br>
<br>
They are full of contradictions and excuses. Perhaps polls for players were put up on all of these issues. Did I just miss them? I never knew my Monk was a better tanker than a warrior. Every mid to high level raid i've been to the warrior was MA and another warrior, pally, or SK was SA.<br>
<br>
In my opinion, and take this with a grain of salt, is many of the changes made to the game are a result of lack of knowledge of what the average players goals and wants actually are. There always seems to be a knee-jerk over-reaction by the designers to right a perceived problem. In some cases perhaps they are right. <br>
<br>
The bottom line with an issue like this is whether the direction taken was the proper one and done in a timely manner. None of these changes are done in a timely manner. Manaburn has been an issue as far back as I can remember. An excuse given with regard to the items a monk can now wear seems thin. What is being suggested is we are all going to pay for their mistakes. We have played the game handed to us but because of mistakes they made a year ago we all pay now. At very best thats very bad customer service. At the worst it simply shows they truly don't understand or take the time to understand what the consequences for their actions and additions are.<br>
<br>
I truly never knew the Monk class was broken. Perhaps my head was in the sand.<br>
<br>
I play and have played pretty much every class since the first days of EQ. And nothing has changed. All I would ask of them is to apologize less and think ahead more. Its a simple idea that would save them and us a lot of grief. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
