<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The mitigation disparity (or equality) is not helped when most/all of your non visible slots have the same items in them that the warrior most likely has (spider fur, velium fire wedding rings, BSEEs), and most likely the 'best' haste option for both of you is probably the same item as well (SCHW).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And that's exactly the problem as perceived by the plate classes even pre-50! Monks were given higher Defense caps, better Block/Dodge (vs. Parry) caps, and the level-based AC boost specifically to offset their low-AC armor (Mesh!) available back in 1999. I wasn't playing a Monk back then (Scalia was created as a foray in pure melee-dom at the time Velious was released) but I remember how it was back then.<br>
<br>
But now, with Kunark, Velious and Luclin out, we have light weight ALL/ALL armor that is readily available to all melees classes including Monks, so what's there to offset? Monks get to wear the same armor as Warriors plus get the benefit of better defensive skills and class-based AC boost! And that's long before the AC soft cap and mitigation being broken become an issue.<br>
<br>
So compared to my Warrior friend, I end up having at least equal if not better tanking abilities, higher DPS with comparable weapons, self-healing every 6 minutes and much better pulling abilities with FD. His biggest advantage is having more HP, which makes Clerics' CH more efficient, but we all know that.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Even with all of that, I am rather suprised he 'is nowhere close to the 1000' ac mark fully buffed. My paladin was pretty ghetto (two pieces of valorium, treeweave, etc.), yet shortly after Kunark he could get over 900 AC without a shield at level 49, with 10 points less defense than the warrior should have.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Unfortunately, I don't have my GL's Magelo address, so I can't go over it piece by piece, but the end result is &lt;1,000AC with Clerical buffs <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, there is no question that the equilibrium changes yet again if we look at Monks in sub-par gear vs. heavily twinked plate classes. For example, my Druid (guild porter) was helping a level 47 Human Monk get to 48 in CC the other day and he had 870ish AC and 1300HP. He wasn't exactly a mana sink, but I wouldn't want him as the MT in an XP group either. On the other hand, a MB-capable Wizard friend of mine has a level 46 SK twink and he broke the &quot;1K AC unbuffed&quot; barrier at level 43. But then it would be comparing apples and oranges <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=71792 target=_blank>Scalia</a> /  <a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=71783 target =_blank>Gluon</a> on E'ci</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uthornyeq.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ThornyEQ</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(10/11/02 2:13:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ac soft cap</span><hr size=1> I have a monk, but he's low-level &quot;fun&quot; character. Still, I hope this post is not taken to have any negative remarks towards monks, because I'm not intending any.<br>
<br>
Well, here goes...perhaps Verant should consider finally allowing people to see the separate avoidance and mitigation portions of AC? It will change nothing in real terms, but it could be a balm for frayed nerves. Then, at least, monks could see that their avoidance AC far outpaces a warrior's avoidance AC; maybe +AGI items will even become &quot;useful&quot; again, as I believe AGI is a part of avoidance AC (correct me if I'm wrong).<br>
<br>
We can &quot;kind of&quot; already see this in a way by taking off all our armor; what is left (natural AC, defensive skills, etc) is likely most, if not all, avoidance AC. The armor itself would be mostly mitigation AC. Why not make the numbers &quot;official&quot; and put them up directly on the screen, where we can see them easily?<br>
<br>
Lastly, this is a case of closing the barn door after the horses have bolted, but perhaps instead of adding in gear like 60 AC monk pants there should be gear that is of a more reasonable AC, but includes raw +avoidance stats (above and beyond AGI or dodge/block modifiers). That way, the gear is desirable because you get hit less, yet AC is kept to a more reasonable level.<br>
<br>
I dunno, just suggestions.<br>
